definition.val: A spatiotemporal region encompassing some part of the life cycle of an organism.
Temporal interval that defines pig life from the prenatal stage until late adult stage.
Pig life cycle that starts with fertilization and ends at birth.

comments: Embryo develops in 115 days (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Sus_scrofa). We follow embryologic feature description as provided by https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Book_-_Embryology_of_the_Pig, based on the book from BM Patten, Embryology of the Pig (1951).

definition.val: Pig developmental stage that covers the period from birth until about 11 months old, when individuals reach sexual maturity.

comments: Pig reach sexual maturity by 768 days of age for male, 334 days for female. While achieving sexual maturity much earlier, males do not typically mate until they are about 5 years old (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Sus_scrofa).

definition.val: Pig developmental stage that covers the period from birth until about 2 months old, at which point individuals wean.

comments: Age of weaning is 56 days (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Sus_scrofa). Piglets are highly precocious and neonates appear with open eyes, good muscle tone and well developed skin and hair (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874755). Within minutes of being born, or sometimes seconds, they will attempt to suckle. The piglets are born with sharp teeth and fight to develop a teat order as the anterior teats produce a greater quantity of milk (see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piglet_%28animal%29).

definition.val: Pig developmental stage that covers the period from about 2 months old, when individuals wean, until about 11 months old, when individuals reach sexual maturity.

comments: Pig reach sexual maturity by 768 days of age for male, 334 days for female. While achieving sexual maturity much earlier, males do not typically mate until they are about 5 years old (see http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Sus_scrofa).

definition.val: Pig developmental stage that refers to a sexually mature adult pig, which is usually over 11 months old.
Mature stage that refers to a pig who is over 11 months old and under 8 years old, the limit before geriatric age in the literature.

comments: Geriatric pigs are usually defined as animals with 8 years of age and older (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12762388).

Prenatal stage that starts at fertilization time and ends at about days 45 of gestation, when fetal weight gain accelerates.

comments: We define pig early and late embryonic stages based on fetal growth (see https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15446468). Pig embryo begins to attach to the uterus on days 1314 of pregnancy (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Pig_Development#Normal_Stages). At that stage, this is a 6-somite pig embryo (see https://embryology.med.unsw.edu.au/embryology/index.php/Book_-_Embryology_of_the_Pig_5).

definition.val: Prenatal stage that refers to fetal pig development over 45 days of gestation.

comments: We define pig early and late embryonic stages based on fetal growth (see https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15446468).

definition.val: Pig fetal stage when the developing limb begins to grow out from the flank.

comments: This stage is defined at embryonic day 20 during pig development (see https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov//pubmed/28335721).

definition.val: Pig fetal stage when the developing limb looks like a semicircle that is as long as it is wide.

comments: This stage is defined at embryonic day 22 during pig development (see https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov//pubmed/28335721).

definition.val: Pig fetal stage when the developing limb looks like a hand-plate.

comments: This stage is defined at embryonic day 26 during pig development (see https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov//pubmed/28335721).

definition.val: Pig developmental stage that covers the period from birth until late adulthood.
Nursing stage that refers to a piglet which is over 1 week old and not weaned.
Embryonic stage at which the ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm develop into the internal organs of the organism.
A stage at which the organism is a single cell produced by means of sexual reproduction.
Embryonic stage consisting of division of cells in the early embryo.

comments: The different cells derived from cleavage are called blastomeres and form a compact mass called the morula. Cleavage ends with the formation of the blastula.

definition.val: Embryonic stage that is an early stage of embryonic development in animals and is produced by cleavage of a fertilized ovum, with formation of a central fluid-filled cavity called the blastocoel.

Embryonic stage defined by complex and coordinated series of cellular movements that occurs at the end of cleavage, resulting in the formation of the three primary germ layers, ectoderm, mesoderm and endoderm.
Embryonic stage defined by formation of a tube from the flat layer of ectodermal cells known as the neural plate.
